FeedPackage.Description: Speedy Object-Relational Mapper for Microsoft Sql Server
FeedPackage.Summary: This solution is a micro Object-Relational Mapper aimed at speed. The speed comes from less "micro managing" of code going on, which makes the framework much faster. The great thing about OR-M Data Entities are the two different data context's you can use. DbSqlContext is for those familiar with Sql. DbSqlContext is a derivative of Entity Framework, the difference is there are no DbSets to declare. Instead your classes (tables) will perform the direct manipluation . Also, there is DbEntityContext, which is almost an exact mirror of Entity Framework, just lighter and different inner workings. Simple operations are the same such as saving and deleting.
FeedPackage.Tags: ORM OR-M Entity Framework EF O/RM Sql

12. First will now throw an error if no data rows exist from the query
13. Because of added support for foreign keys, all queries must now use Linq

FeedPackage.Description: This solution is a micro Object-Relational Mapper aimed at speed. OR-M Data Entities does less "micro managing" of code, which makes the framework much faster.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
Version 3's core was all rewritten to make it faster than version two. It contains lots of optimizations and a faster lamba resolver. The biggest new addition is the ability to use lazy loading. This can be useful for large/complex databases. Please see the configuration and lazy loading sections for the new items.
New Items:
Concurrency Checking Lazy Loading Max Length Attribute Configure Default Insert Values OnSqlGenerated (Event which allows you to see the sql that was generated along with its parameters)
Warning: Contains breaking changes if upgrading from v2

FeedPackage.Description: ORM Framework - Easy and simple to use.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
.Net Framework Supports SQL Server by default.
Start with just n simple steps: 1) Create a class to represent a database table/model. 2) Derive it from AbstractEntity. 3) Create properties to represents the fields for that model. 4) Decorate the properties with [DbField, DbKey, DbIdentity, DbRequired] [DbField] -> Indicates that the property is a field; [DbKey] -> Well... its a key... [DbIdentity] -> The field is the Identity field increasing automatically; [DbRequired] -> Allows the framework to check for the required fields before executing SQL commands. 5) Create a ConnectionString entry in the app.config/web.config file with the name DbConnection. [DbConnection | DbConnection-[MachineName]]
